We know the kind of nominee Donald Trump will try to get on the U.S. Supreme Court. He's already released two lists of potential nominees, compiled with the help of the conservative Federalist Society and Heritage Foundation.

They include nine sitting justices on state supreme courts as well as federal judges who've drawn attention in conservative circles for their decisions favoring states' rights and federalism, often to the consternation of civil-rights activists who advocate for federal protections against discrimination.
